and The Last of Us Part II.

57
00:02:25,539 --> 00:02:33,305
I wanted to talk to you guys today about showing your characters in context and how that can

58
00:02:33,325 --> 00:02:39,190
avoid some pitfalls of stereotypes.

59
00:02:51,724 --> 00:02:55,205
relying on cliches and sort of tropes that go into character design.

60
00:02:55,845 --> 00:02:58,726
So before we concentrate on this, I wanted to tell a little story.

61
00:02:59,246 --> 00:03:03,588
The other day I was tasked with concepting a tough guy,

62
00:03:03,648 --> 00:03:06,468
a strong, intimidating, physical character.

63
00:03:07,789 --> 00:03:11,470
So I went about it the normal way, probably most of us here have been taught.

64
00:03:11,870 --> 00:03:14,171
How many here are concept artists at the moment?

65
00:03:15,691 --> 00:03:18,992
Oh, sweet. And character artists? Yeah, awesome.

66
00:03:19,743 --> 00:03:21,784
So essentially, for the most part,

67
00:03:21,824 --> 00:03:24,026
we're taught to present our characters in a lineup.

68
00:03:24,086 --> 00:03:25,507
It's a flat background,

69
00:03:26,967 --> 00:03:28,789
showing different costume designs as we go.

70
00:03:29,389 --> 00:03:31,790
So I did my tough guy, as we all do,

71
00:03:31,871 --> 00:03:36,313
big barrel chest, square jaw, big pose, clinch fists,

72
00:03:37,394 --> 00:03:38,835
and presented my costumes.

73
00:03:39,816 --> 00:03:42,237
One of the costumes had him wearing glasses,

74
00:03:43,158 --> 00:03:44,859
and I was showing it to a group of people,

75
00:03:44,979 --> 00:03:47,220
creative directors, designers, and a bunch of other people.

76
00:03:48,907 --> 00:03:51,550
Their reaction to the glasses was interesting to me.

77
00:03:51,590 --> 00:03:53,271
When they saw that, they said, no, no, no, no,

78
00:03:53,332 --> 00:03:54,493
he can't be wearing glasses.

79
00:03:55,273 --> 00:03:57,355
That's not indicative of a tough guy.

80
00:03:57,976 --> 00:03:59,778
And instantly alarm bells are ringing for me

81
00:04:00,519 --> 00:04:02,901
that I'm not showing these people enough.

82
00:04:02,921 --> 00:04:04,362
They're not seeing enough of the puzzle

83
00:04:04,462 --> 00:04:05,964
for them to make a decision.

84
00:04:06,638 --> 00:04:10,320
about what this character is going to be and what they're going to wear and how we're going to present them.

85
00:04:10,661 --> 00:04:13,082
They're basically trying to tell the whole story at a glance,

86
00:04:14,442 --> 00:04:16,203
based on shape, language and everything else.

87
00:04:16,544 --> 00:04:17,564
Which is great for a lot of games.

88
00:04:17,764 --> 00:04:19,705
You know, Team Fortress 2, at a glance.

89
00:04:19,725 --> 00:04:21,526
The big heavy guy moves slow, hits hard.

90
00:04:21,926 --> 00:04:23,667
But when you're working on games like Uncharted 4,

91
00:04:24,868 --> 00:04:28,950
The Last of Us, where the intentions of the character are totally ambiguous,

92
00:04:29,730 --> 00:04:33,052
or we don't even want that character to be reading that way at this point,

93
00:04:33,072 --> 00:04:34,913
but we want them to read another way at another point.

94
00:04:35,775 --> 00:04:38,537
all of these kind of cliches and stereotypes sort of fall apart.

95
00:04:38,697 --> 00:04:41,519
So, today I'm going to show a new process that I've been using.

96
00:04:41,559 --> 00:04:43,801
It's still a work in progress, but I'm getting some good results,

97
00:04:44,081 --> 00:04:46,302
including that character now wears glasses.

98
00:04:48,824 --> 00:04:53,107
The first thing is our games are realistic character narrative-driven games.

99
00:04:53,607 --> 00:04:56,289
So, the first thing I do is I sit down and I plot out my narrative.

100
00:04:56,770 --> 00:05:00,472
So, at the moment we're going to use the storyline of Stephen King's Carrie.

101
00:05:01,293 --> 00:05:03,914
Spoilers, if you haven't seen Carrie, I'm about to spoil a story for you.

102
00:05:06,224 --> 00:05:11,027
about a telekinetic, magic-powered girl, high school girl.

103
00:05:11,628 --> 00:05:14,629
She goes to school, she's ostracized, she's bullied,

104
00:05:15,730 --> 00:05:17,071
and eventually she's pushed too far

105
00:05:17,131 --> 00:05:20,633
and she murders all her peers with her telekinetic powers.

106
00:05:21,454 --> 00:05:24,516
So this is what I do, is I basically plot out my plot line,

107
00:05:24,536 --> 00:05:26,837
and you can see these little storyboards over here.

108
00:05:27,342 --> 00:05:31,405
The first one, she starts at a new school, she's optimistic, she's happy, she's picked

109
00:05:31,465 --> 00:05:34,868
on a little bit, she starts to be intimidated and starts to be scared.

110
00:05:35,188 --> 00:05:37,810
She's ostracized by her peers, so she's alone.

111
00:05:39,111 --> 00:05:42,834
She's then physically assaulted, and in Carrie there's the famous blood pouring on the head.

112
00:05:42,894 --> 00:05:44,395
I just had her in this one getting beat up.

113
00:05:45,376 --> 00:05:52,181
And then she unleashes her revenge and is empowered and murders everyone with her telekinetic

114
00:05:52,221 --> 00:05:52,541
powers.

115
00:05:53,042 --> 00:05:54,223
So this is the first thing I do.

116
00:05:56,202 --> 00:05:59,744
I gather reference and create a little line up based on that.

117
00:05:59,804 --> 00:06:03,627
So we're looking at a whole bunch of reference here and already we can see pitfalls that

118
00:06:03,648 --> 00:06:04,788
we probably want to avoid.

119
00:06:04,848 --> 00:06:10,513
There's some really great characters in Ralph Macchio for the outsiders and some other complex

120
00:06:10,553 --> 00:06:10,973
characters.

121
00:06:11,013 --> 00:06:12,474
There's Carrie over there in the top left.

122
00:06:13,635 --> 00:06:17,478
And then you've got some pretty corny ones that aren't funny until you've had 20 beers

123
00:06:17,538 --> 00:06:19,820
like Revenge of the Nerds and some other ones like that.

124
00:06:19,960 --> 00:06:20,481
Breakfast Club.

125
00:06:21,905 --> 00:06:24,667
At this point, you can already see that there's going to be things that people are going to

126
00:06:24,687 --> 00:06:26,028
respond to instantly.

127
00:06:26,228 --> 00:06:29,329
And if you wanted to take the cheap way out, sure, you could dress them like Revenge of

128
00:06:29,349 --> 00:06:29,709
the Nerds.

129
00:06:29,970 --> 00:06:35,012
Everyone knows that person's going to be ostracized according to some shape language invented

130
00:06:35,052 --> 00:06:35,773
in the 80s.

131
00:06:37,634 --> 00:06:41,896
So I create a little lineup at this point, going from one side to the other, trying to

132
00:06:41,916 --> 00:06:44,957
keep it fairly natural, but there's a few characters in there that you feel in the right

133
00:06:44,997 --> 00:06:48,299
circumstances might be ostracized.

134
00:06:48,885 --> 00:06:54,009
I've chosen this character because she's cute, she's small, she's not physically empowered,

135
00:06:55,269 --> 00:06:59,252
and hopefully because she is cute, you're going to feel some kind of protective instinct

136
00:06:59,272 --> 00:06:59,492
to her.

137
00:07:00,273 --> 00:07:05,216
So the next thing I do is I choose one of my plot points, because this is going to be

138
00:07:05,236 --> 00:07:05,756
our costume.

139
00:07:05,776 --> 00:07:08,338
These are thematical beats throughout the game.

140
00:07:08,358 --> 00:07:11,740
For us, it's very cinematic, so I'm always picturing it like a film.

141
00:07:14,102 --> 00:07:17,764
What is this person going to be wearing in each scene starts to matter.

142
00:07:19,382 --> 00:07:20,442
Oh, there's one missing here.

143
00:07:20,462 --> 00:07:22,382
So I've chosen a character at this point.

144
00:07:24,203 --> 00:07:25,943
So let's look at these ones

145
00:07:25,963 --> 00:07:27,784
and we choose a few of these scenes

146
00:07:28,584 --> 00:07:30,225
and we start slotting in our characters.

147
00:07:30,805 --> 00:07:34,386
And we can see already that less and less has to be,

148
00:07:35,286 --> 00:07:36,526
there's less and less pressure

149
00:07:36,887 --> 00:07:39,087
on what the character is wearing in isolation.

150
00:07:39,587 --> 00:07:41,008
Because we can already see from this scene

151
00:07:41,028 --> 00:07:44,329
that she's pressured by the way she's framed.

152
00:07:44,369 --> 00:07:46,349
The bully is filling the majority of the frame.

153
00:07:46,389 --> 00:07:47,750
She's squeezed over to one side.

154
00:07:48,080 --> 00:07:49,721
We see expression, we see lighting.

155
00:07:50,282 --> 00:07:51,943
So the creative director and art directors,

156
00:07:51,963 --> 00:07:53,044
when they look at these shots,

157
00:07:53,705 --> 00:07:56,287
are able to understand a little bit more about the character

158
00:07:56,908 --> 00:07:58,850
and they don't have to rely on so many tropes.

159
00:08:01,172 --> 00:08:02,994
So as we go through the shot, you realize,

160
00:08:03,094 --> 00:08:05,636
hey, maybe some of these character types

161
00:08:05,696 --> 00:08:06,697
are a little bit heavy handed.

162
00:08:07,270 --> 00:08:08,671
So for me, I chose this one here.

163
00:08:08,711 --> 00:08:09,792
I felt she was natural.

164
00:08:09,872 --> 00:08:12,415
She still looks, she still looks scared.

165
00:08:12,955 --> 00:08:15,478
Our framing technique has made sure she looks pressured.

166
00:08:15,818 --> 00:08:17,800
Our camera is with her at chest height.

167
00:08:17,860 --> 00:08:21,203
So as an audience, we understand that we're with her

168
00:08:21,263 --> 00:08:22,084
in this experience.

169
00:08:24,306 --> 00:08:25,927
And at this point, you can already see

170
00:08:25,948 --> 00:08:27,789
that someone has to make a decision about a costume.

171
00:08:28,491 --> 00:08:31,373
looking at these has a little bit more information.

172
00:08:31,693 --> 00:08:34,014
So all of a sudden, these are less impactful.

173
00:08:34,194 --> 00:08:36,135
This is just more like, hey, this is the blueprint.

174
00:08:36,375 --> 00:08:38,517
This might even be the first step of the character sheet.

175
00:08:39,197 --> 00:08:41,058
These are what the creative directors are gonna look at.

176
00:08:42,499 --> 00:08:44,760
So we can even just like swap the character out altogether.

177
00:08:44,780 --> 00:08:48,442
It doesn't have to be a small, cute girl anymore.

178
00:08:48,642 --> 00:08:50,823
It can just be this dude, this Ralph Manchio looking dude.

179
00:08:51,164 --> 00:08:53,125
And still he looks pressured, he looks bullied.

180
00:08:53,465 --> 00:08:55,446
All of a sudden, the stereotypes are completely gone.

181
00:08:57,574 --> 00:09:01,215
So from there, if we go back and we look at our whole lineup,

182
00:09:02,115 --> 00:09:05,896
I go through each scene and I start blocking shots off.

183
00:09:06,537 --> 00:09:07,537
So if we look at these, we've got,

184
00:09:07,857 --> 00:09:09,157
she starts a new day at school.

185
00:09:10,278 --> 00:09:11,778
You know, it's a pretty standard framing.

186
00:09:12,218 --> 00:09:13,819
She looks nice, she's having a good time.

187
00:09:13,859 --> 00:09:15,099
The camera's a little bit low.

188
00:09:15,179 --> 00:09:16,579
She's slightly empowered.

189
00:09:16,959 --> 00:09:17,240
Perfect.

190
00:09:18,020 --> 00:09:19,080
Next shot, she's getting bullied.

191
00:09:19,280 --> 00:09:20,060
Just went through that one.

192
00:09:21,300 --> 00:09:22,641
Next shot, she's ostracized.

193
00:09:22,881 --> 00:09:24,261
I mean, these are super simple things.

194
