you will not be able to look in the mirror the same way as you do today.

601
00:31:38,806 --> 00:31:41,049
So I would like to introduce Laurel from Blizzard Entertainment.

602
00:31:47,956 --> 00:31:49,757
Hi everybody, my name is Laurel Austin.

603
00:31:49,957 --> 00:31:51,938
I am a principal artist at Blizzard Entertainment

604
00:31:52,338 --> 00:31:54,659
and I'm here to talk about expressive faces

605
00:31:54,839 --> 00:31:56,940
for your characters in concept art and illustration.

606
00:31:57,701 --> 00:32:00,062
At Blizzard, primarily I do marketing art

607
00:32:00,122 --> 00:32:03,643
for games like Hearthstone, Starcraft, Diablo,

608
00:32:03,703 --> 00:32:04,544
World of Warcraft.

609
00:32:06,365 --> 00:32:07,305
And before I came to Blizzard,

610
00:32:07,345 --> 00:32:09,746
I began my career as a concept artist at Splash Damage

611
00:32:09,806 --> 00:32:11,367
where I was the character concept artist

612
00:32:11,607 --> 00:32:13,988
on the post-apocalyptic first-person shooter called Brink.

613
00:32:15,484 --> 00:32:19,605
More recently, I've done a lot of artwork for Blizzard's 2.5D cinematics, including

614
00:32:19,725 --> 00:32:24,867
the series Burdens of Shaohao, and some art from Lords of War and Harbingers.

615
00:32:25,627 --> 00:32:26,868
These are sort of unusual projects.

616
00:32:26,908 --> 00:32:31,449
They're kind of short films that are made up of a series of illustrations, and to these

617
00:32:31,489 --> 00:32:35,531
illustrations our team adds kind of slight animation and parallax.

618
00:32:35,731 --> 00:32:40,573
Not full animation, but somewhere between a motion comic and a full 2D animation.

619
00:32:41,711 --> 00:32:43,812
And I've always loved painting faces,

620
00:32:44,493 --> 00:32:46,254
but it was on these projects in particular

621
00:32:46,334 --> 00:32:47,674
that I really came to understand

622
00:32:47,734 --> 00:32:49,295
how a focus on facial expressions

623
00:32:49,595 --> 00:32:50,916
can really enhance storytelling.

624
00:32:51,817 --> 00:32:53,498
In each of these shorts, you follow a character

625
00:32:53,538 --> 00:32:55,499
through one of the most pivotal moments in their lives.

626
00:32:56,699 --> 00:32:58,140
And it's important to spend a lot of energy

627
00:32:58,200 --> 00:32:59,941
making the character's emotional state really clear.

628
00:33:01,170 --> 00:33:05,413
A well-chosen expression can put your character into their context, tell their story, and

629
00:33:05,453 --> 00:33:06,193
make them seem real.

630
00:33:06,313 --> 00:33:10,816
And in my career as an artist, a well-chosen expression is what I've found to be one of

631
00:33:10,836 --> 00:33:13,137
the most powerful tools I've found to connect with viewers.

632
00:33:14,278 --> 00:33:17,540
And I found that this understanding has changed the way that I approach character art in general.

633
00:33:18,220 --> 00:33:22,763
So now whether I'm doing concept art or illustration, I try to imply as much story and character

634
00:33:22,803 --> 00:33:23,844
in the faces as possible.

635
00:33:24,544 --> 00:33:24,965
So today...

636
00:33:26,489 --> 00:33:29,452
So today I'm going to share with you a way I found helpful to break down expressions

637
00:33:29,572 --> 00:33:32,355
into their constituent parts so that they can be used as an artistic tool.

638
00:33:33,156 --> 00:33:36,799
Most of us are roughly familiar with how psychologists break down the basic emotions.

639
00:33:37,219 --> 00:33:40,242
There's some disagreement on the particulars of this, but for the purposes of this talk,

640
00:33:40,322 --> 00:33:42,224
I'm going to focus on six basic expressions.

641
00:33:43,205 --> 00:33:50,853
This is happiness, sadness, anger, disgust, fear, and surprise.

642
00:33:51,693 --> 00:33:59,270
Expressions themselves are constellations of many small facial movements, and we should think of these small movements as the building blocks for our characters' performances.

643
00:34:01,377 --> 00:34:05,260
We know a lot of this stuff intuitively, but in real life, it can actually be quite difficult

644
00:34:05,300 --> 00:34:06,922
to see all the elements of an expression.

645
00:34:07,402 --> 00:34:13,087
We're so used to reading each other's faces in our daily lives that when we see an expression

646
00:34:13,147 --> 00:34:17,630
on another person's face, we often just directly perceive the emotion that it means to us,

647
00:34:17,771 --> 00:34:20,032
and we don't notice all the little elements that make it up.

648
00:34:20,633 --> 00:34:24,716
Consequently, it can be hard to visualize exactly what an emotion looks like.

649
00:34:25,397 --> 00:34:28,439
If you ask people what happiness looks like, most people would just say a smile.

650
00:34:29,358 --> 00:34:31,679
But as most artists know, there's a lot more to it than that.

651
00:34:32,099 --> 00:34:34,979
So bear with me while I take a few minutes to break down the basic expressions,

652
00:34:35,540 --> 00:34:36,860
and let's look at some of the elements.

653
00:34:38,280 --> 00:34:41,781
Here, you have the expected upward movement of the corners of the mouth.

654
00:34:42,322 --> 00:34:44,602
But what people often don't notice is that when that happens,

655
00:34:44,682 --> 00:34:46,483
the nostrils kind of get pulled along with it.

656
00:34:46,563 --> 00:34:50,684
The muscles of the mouth pull aside and pull the nostrils to the side as well.

657
00:34:51,649 --> 00:34:55,992
And the third thing in a smile is really the rays of the lower eyelids.

658
00:34:56,653 --> 00:35:01,757
This is what psychologists call a Duchenne smile, and it's the hallmark of a true and

659
00:35:01,817 --> 00:35:05,420
genuine happy smile, rather than one that's kind of weird or fake.

660
00:35:07,221 --> 00:35:10,985
And when we dial up the intensity, all the characteristics just get a bit more extreme.

661
00:35:11,005 --> 00:35:15,268
And you can get new elements added, like a raise to the eyebrows or an opening of the

662
00:35:15,308 --> 00:35:15,488
mouth.

663
00:35:17,152 --> 00:35:19,913
With sadness, most people know the downward movement

664
00:35:19,953 --> 00:35:20,853
of the corners of the mouth,

665
00:35:21,453 --> 00:35:23,254
but one thing people don't often notice about frowns

666
00:35:23,274 --> 00:35:25,155
is that the downward curve is partly created

667
00:35:25,195 --> 00:35:27,355
by an upward movement of the middle of the lower lip.

668
00:35:27,915 --> 00:35:29,276
In addition, the center of the eyebrows

669
00:35:29,336 --> 00:35:30,836
raises up and slightly contracts.

670
00:35:31,936 --> 00:35:33,877
Sadness is also a particularly good example

671
00:35:33,897 --> 00:35:36,558
of how small changes can make a really big difference

672
00:35:36,638 --> 00:35:39,139
in the impression that the face gives.

673
00:35:39,879 --> 00:35:41,639
It doesn't take much to change the impact

674
00:35:41,659 --> 00:35:42,520
of an expression at all.

675
00:35:43,264 --> 00:35:47,047
Here, we barely move the face at all, but by adding more tension to the mouth and brow

676
00:35:47,107 --> 00:35:50,549
and some tears welling up in his eyes, it adds a lot more intensity to the expression.

677
00:35:50,569 --> 00:35:54,772
And one thing the game artists are often called upon to deliver is anger.

678
00:35:55,413 --> 00:35:56,834
Mild anger is relatively simple.

679
00:35:56,974 --> 00:35:58,115
Our guy here looks a bit peeved.

680
00:35:58,823 --> 00:36:03,166
His lips are pursed, his jaw is kind of clenched and thrust forward, his eyebrows go down,

681
00:36:03,466 --> 00:36:04,647
and his nostrils move upwards.

682
00:36:05,407 --> 00:36:07,809
And if you intensify anger, some surprising things start to happen.

683
00:36:07,849 --> 00:36:11,932
You get the obvious increase in the upper face tension where you get the lines of the

684
00:36:11,952 --> 00:36:13,613
different muscles smushed against one another.

685
00:36:14,293 --> 00:36:17,075
But in the lower face, I want you to see what happens in the mouth and neck.

686
00:36:17,915 --> 00:36:22,057
The tension in the neck and the lips are deeply intertwined and are mostly caused by a muscle

687
00:36:22,077 --> 00:36:22,838
called the platysma.

688
00:36:22,858 --> 00:36:24,118
It's actually one of my favorite muscles.

689
00:36:24,559 --> 00:36:30,983
And it lies as a sheet in your neck that actually goes from the bottom of your face right over

690
00:36:31,023 --> 00:36:33,884
your clavicles, when it's right at the surface under your skin.

691
00:36:34,585 --> 00:36:39,127
And this is the striated lines that you often see in comic book heroes, when they're really

692
00:36:39,167 --> 00:36:40,928
straining and punching each other in comic books.

693
00:36:43,891 --> 00:36:47,235
So anytime you get a downward movement in the corners of the mouth, this muscle is activated,

694
00:36:47,255 --> 00:36:48,336
and that's when you see those lines.

695
00:36:49,978 --> 00:36:54,983
With disgust, it's good to think about it as your face trying to escape or expel whatever

696
00:36:55,023 --> 00:36:56,224
the disgusting stimulus is.

697
00:36:56,785 --> 00:36:59,447
Here you get the mouth and the nose squishing upwards,

698
00:36:59,807 --> 00:37:01,288
the corners of the mouth moving down,

699
00:37:01,648 --> 00:37:02,709
and you get a squint to the eyes.

700
00:37:02,769 --> 00:37:04,370
The squint to the eyes can include the eyebrows,

701
00:37:04,410 --> 00:37:05,310
but it doesn't have to.

702
00:37:06,131 --> 00:37:07,952
With extreme disgust, you again get

703
00:37:07,992 --> 00:37:09,192
all the features intensifying,

704
00:37:09,693 --> 00:37:11,274
but you might also get the tongue protruding

705
00:37:11,314 --> 00:37:13,135
as though it's trying to spit out something gross.

706
00:37:14,255 --> 00:37:17,217
With fear, you get a widening of the eyes,

707
00:37:17,237 --> 00:37:18,538
a flare of the nostrils,

708
00:37:19,078 --> 00:37:21,980
an upward movement to the eyebrows, and inwards as well.

709
00:37:22,760 --> 00:37:24,401
And you get a bit of a downward movement

710
00:37:24,421 --> 00:37:25,261
to the corners of the mouth.

711
00:37:26,131 --> 00:37:28,813
And when you intensify fear, all that movement becomes more extreme,

712
00:37:29,153 --> 00:37:31,554
and you might also get an opening of the mouth and nose

713
00:37:32,174 --> 00:37:34,036
in something like a gasp or an intake of breath.

714
00:37:34,636 --> 00:37:36,977
This movement of the nose is actually quite distinct

715
00:37:37,037 --> 00:37:38,538
to the one we talked about on happiness,

716
00:37:38,758 --> 00:37:43,601
because this one actually indicates the muscles in the nose taking in breath.

717
00:37:43,681 --> 00:37:44,402
So it's a bit different.

718
00:37:45,737 --> 00:37:48,279
In surprise, the whole face can appear to stretch vertically.

719
00:37:49,180 --> 00:37:52,182
The brow goes straight up, the eyes widen, and the mouth can open.

720
00:37:52,362 --> 00:37:55,804
In this case, even though his jaw is slightly open, his lips are still together.

721
00:37:55,864 --> 00:37:59,646
So you kind of get that surprise face where your lips are still together.

722
00:37:59,666 --> 00:38:05,750
And more extreme surprise, the mouth might open fully and all the elements again become

723
00:38:05,790 --> 00:38:06,451
more exaggerated.

724
00:38:07,174 --> 00:38:08,875
So all of this stuff is pretty simple.

725
00:38:08,915 --> 00:38:10,475
We see people's faces every day.

726
00:38:11,035 --> 00:38:13,096
And we all know that these little constellations

727
00:38:13,316 --> 00:38:15,376
of facial movements can make up these expressions.

728
00:38:15,956 --> 00:38:17,677
But what happens when we start to combine them?

729
00:38:18,017 --> 00:38:19,838
And this is where things really start to get interesting.

730
00:38:20,178 --> 00:38:21,898
We can combine aspects from one expression

731
00:38:21,938 --> 00:38:24,199
to aspects of another, and this is how we create

732
00:38:24,219 --> 00:38:26,119
the most truly interesting and subtle effects.

733
00:38:27,039 --> 00:38:30,780
So if we add aspects of happiness to aspects of surprise,

734
00:38:31,441 --> 00:38:31,941
what do we get?

735
00:38:32,861 --> 00:38:33,401
Free puppies.

736
00:38:35,670 --> 00:38:38,671
Here, his mouth opens and the corners go up,

737
00:38:38,731 --> 00:38:40,132
as you expect from happiness.

738
00:38:40,252 --> 00:38:41,973
His eyebrows raise, as in surprise,

739
00:38:42,353 --> 00:38:45,155
and you get the lower lid raise, indicating that he is indeed

740
00:38:45,215 --> 00:38:46,375
very happy about the puppies.

741
00:38:47,496 --> 00:38:50,897
And then, what happens if we, instead of surprise,

742
00:38:51,058 --> 00:38:51,958
swap out anger?

743
00:38:53,079 --> 00:38:56,740
You get the mouth position is actually identical here.

744
00:38:56,760 --> 00:38:57,921
It is exactly the same.

745
00:38:59,302 --> 00:39:01,163
But his eyebrows contracting make a face

746
00:39:01,183 --> 00:39:02,463
that's due to a very different story.

747
00:39:03,472 --> 00:39:05,513
a story that may or may not have happened to me in high school.

748
00:39:07,354 --> 00:39:10,595
You can even combine the same two expressions in different ways for different effects.

749
00:39:11,555 --> 00:39:15,696
And if we dial back the intensity, you get, adding slight anger to slight happiness, you

750
00:39:15,736 --> 00:39:17,077
get the ever-useful smolder.

751
00:39:18,297 --> 00:39:21,659
This expression is found on box art a lot and occasionally on actual humans.

752
00:39:23,659 --> 00:39:27,080
Here you get the eyebrows contracting a little bit, a bit of the lower lid raised, and a

753
00:39:27,140 --> 00:39:28,201
slight upturn to the mouth.

754
00:39:29,261 --> 00:39:32,102
And sometimes we have a very specific story moment we have to work to.

755
00:39:33,117 --> 00:39:34,443
In this case, surprise and fear.

756
00:39:34,885 --> 00:39:37,496
Let's say your kid backing your car into a mailbox.

757
00:39:38,603 --> 00:39:44,026
Here the mouth opens, the eyes widen, the eyebrows contract as in fear, and the eyebrows

758
00:39:44,086 --> 00:39:44,606
raise more.

759
00:39:44,987 --> 00:39:47,868
Fear is a phrase that actually have a lot, or are actually quite similar expressions

760
00:39:47,928 --> 00:39:49,009
and share a lot of elements.

761
00:39:49,109 --> 00:39:53,872
You have to identify which parts are sort of iconic to each particular expression.

762
00:39:53,932 --> 00:39:57,494
In this case, the eyebrow contraction is very important to indicate fear.

763
00:39:58,334 --> 00:40:01,996
But what if our story changes and we have to add elements of a third expression?

764
00:40:02,577 --> 00:40:03,657
Something like disgust.

765
00:40:04,758 --> 00:40:07,460
Here it might suit a story a bit more like this.

766
00:40:08,998 --> 00:40:11,718
So again, you have an unchanged eye movement.

767
00:40:13,199 --> 00:40:14,539
You have an unchanged eye movement,

768
00:40:15,079 --> 00:40:17,500
because disgust really doesn't come into the eyes a whole lot.

769
00:40:17,900 --> 00:40:20,220
But you get the nose wrinkling, the corners of the mouth

770
00:40:20,240 --> 00:40:21,641
pulling down, and the lips protruding.

771
00:40:21,661 --> 00:40:24,621
But you still have the open mouth, like in Fear

772
00:40:24,661 --> 00:40:25,182
and Surprise.

773
00:40:26,242 --> 00:40:29,162
You can even combine diametrically opposed emotions

774
00:40:29,703 --> 00:40:30,663
to really nice effect.

775
00:40:31,083 --> 00:40:32,363
And it's worth experimenting to see

776
00:40:32,403 --> 00:40:33,383
what sorts of impressions you can

777
00:40:33,423 --> 00:40:36,204
get by adding bits of expressions to one another.

778
00:40:37,885 --> 00:40:40,466
So how do we improve at making expressive faces?

779
00:40:41,866 --> 00:40:42,727
Keep a mirror around.

780
00:40:43,007 --> 00:40:44,827
Pay close attention to the way your own face looks

781
00:40:45,368 --> 00:40:46,588
as you study the basic expressions

782
00:40:46,628 --> 00:40:47,828
and use it to help you try things out.

783
00:40:48,169 --> 00:40:50,790
Justin can attest that I do have a mirror at my desk

784
00:40:50,810 --> 00:40:51,670
for this exact purpose.

785
00:40:53,230 --> 00:40:54,051
Study the anatomy.

786
00:40:54,431 --> 00:40:55,751
There are dozens of muscles in the face.

787
00:40:55,811 --> 00:40:57,332
And while you don't need to know all of them,

788
00:40:57,532 --> 00:40:59,073
knowing the major groups of them will really

789
00:40:59,113 --> 00:41:01,333
help you understand what bits affect one another

790
00:41:01,634 --> 00:41:02,934
and how it all comes together.

791
00:41:06,380 --> 00:41:10,283
Mixing and matching bits of basic expressions is a way I've found helpful to help me understand

792
00:41:10,323 --> 00:41:11,344
more complex expressions.

793
00:41:11,464 --> 00:41:14,346
What I've shown you here is just the tiniest sliver of what you can do.

794
00:41:14,427 --> 00:41:17,889
It's almost like paint in the end, where you can just take little bits of one and add them

795
00:41:17,929 --> 00:41:22,553
to a lot of another, and you get infinite possibilities.

796
00:41:23,013 --> 00:41:26,596
Things like insanity, egotism, impatience, they all just get a bit more flavor if we

797
00:41:26,616 --> 00:41:28,098
can throw in things that are unexpected.

798
00:41:28,778 --> 00:41:32,601
So using this approach to facial expressions has helped me add more layers to my character

799
00:41:32,681 --> 00:41:34,363
art, and I hope you found it helpful too.

