1226
01:03:28,393 --> 01:03:31,995
I would say that the majority of characters I'm drawing at the moment are like t-shirt

1227
01:03:32,156 --> 01:03:32,736
and jeans.

1228
01:03:33,677 --> 01:03:34,217
You know what I mean?

1229
01:03:34,237 --> 01:03:37,860
Like, I just sit around with a lot of photos and sketch them up and like, that's another

1230
01:03:37,880 --> 01:03:38,720
dude in t-shirt and jeans.

1231
01:03:39,060 --> 01:03:39,741
Keep it real subtle.

1232
01:03:40,121 --> 01:03:42,022
That person's going to behave in a certain way.

1233
01:03:42,082 --> 01:03:44,044
The tough guy one is a really interesting narrative.

1234
01:03:44,084 --> 01:03:45,585
We were talking about it over lunch.

1235
01:03:46,025 --> 01:03:48,447
You know, Joe Pesci is one of my favorite tough guys.

1236
01:03:49,047 --> 01:03:51,449
If I did him in a lineup of tough guys, no one's going to pick him.

1237
01:03:52,030 --> 01:03:55,994
But when you're in that scene and there's that tension and he's scaring the hell out

1238
01:03:56,014 --> 01:03:58,997
of everyone, then that comes across.

1239
01:03:59,638 --> 01:04:04,843
So I don't know, to answer your question, thematically there's some really nice things

1240
01:04:04,863 --> 01:04:11,510
you can play to in a game as subtle as The Last of Us, but my intention is always to

1241
01:04:11,710 --> 01:04:15,634
support everything else that's going on and not to distract from it.

1242
01:04:16,630 --> 01:04:17,411
Yeah.

1243
01:04:17,651 --> 01:04:18,031
Oh, no.

1244
01:04:18,271 --> 01:04:18,912
Go.

1245
01:04:19,032 --> 01:04:23,275
I think it really depends on the narrative of the game as well, or the narrative of anything

1246
01:04:23,295 --> 01:04:27,617
you're doing, and the needs of that narrative, and how viewers are supposed to feel about

1247
01:04:27,637 --> 01:04:29,098
that narrative while they're experiencing it.

1248
01:04:30,919 --> 01:04:34,742
And you sort of have, like, if you have to concept it, like a nerdy character, you're

1249
01:04:34,762 --> 01:04:37,484
like, well, nerds have glasses, so I'll put them in glasses.

1250
01:04:37,644 --> 01:04:42,027
And that's sort of, like, it's obvious, it may be the right thing to do, but it's not

1251
01:04:42,107 --> 01:04:43,367
so much that you have to, like...

1252
01:04:44,187 --> 01:04:47,008
do like totally be like, no, nerds can't have glasses

1253
01:04:47,028 --> 01:04:47,909
because they always have glasses.

1254
01:04:48,369 --> 01:04:52,231
Like it's not, it's more like, do whatever,

1255
01:04:52,251 --> 01:04:54,191
do what you're doing, but do it with intention.

1256
01:04:54,271 --> 01:04:57,513
Like say, the character, the audience has to feel this way.

1257
01:04:58,233 --> 01:05:01,094
So my choices are going towards that.

1258
01:05:01,314 --> 01:05:05,696
So it's like, if I want a character to, again,

1259
01:05:05,756 --> 01:05:07,857
feel vulnerable, make them physically small.

1260
01:05:08,397 --> 01:05:09,238
If you want them to,

1261
01:05:11,812 --> 01:05:17,654
blend in, maybe they have, they don't contain any bright colors, maybe all the values are

1262
01:05:17,674 --> 01:05:21,395
sort of close together and so when they're put into their context they sort of blend

1263
01:05:21,435 --> 01:05:21,995
in a little bit more.

1264
01:05:22,015 --> 01:05:26,977
So it's thinking about all of those things and making a character whatever style it's

1265
01:05:27,057 --> 01:05:30,238
in to be unique and whatever it needs to be for its context.

1266
01:05:32,487 --> 01:05:37,893
I was just going to say that I love looking at dogs as good inspiration for character

1267
01:05:37,933 --> 01:05:43,640
design in terms of you can have really shitty little dogs and really sweet little dogs and

1268
01:05:43,680 --> 01:05:46,503
the physicality of them is not really...

1269
01:05:47,524 --> 01:05:49,904
it does not really define who they are as a character,

1270
01:05:50,025 --> 01:05:52,085
and it's great to think of character designs that same way.

1271
01:05:52,125 --> 01:05:53,665
It's like the acting and animation,

1272
01:05:53,765 --> 01:05:55,805
which again is why you involve those teams,

1273
01:05:56,326 --> 01:05:57,906
can bring so much to those characters

1274
01:05:58,026 --> 01:06:00,546
and can actually play against the expectations

1275
01:06:00,606 --> 01:06:02,807
that the audience has in really interesting ways.

1276
01:06:02,827 --> 01:06:07,567
That's awesome.

1277
01:06:10,368 --> 01:06:11,188
Does that answer your question?

1278
01:06:12,428 --> 01:06:14,069
Absolutely, I was just standing here

1279
01:06:14,089 --> 01:06:16,109
to encourage the responses continuing.

1280
01:06:16,169 --> 01:06:16,729
Thank you for that.

1281
01:06:18,005 --> 01:06:21,506
It'd be a blast to hear from the whole panel if you'd like to share some thoughts as well.

1282
01:06:22,487 --> 01:06:23,908
Not to eat up the whole time frame for us.

1283
01:06:23,928 --> 01:06:25,008
Is this thing on? Okay.

1284
01:06:26,709 --> 01:06:33,172
You know, one of the things that I've experimented a lot with is basing character design on shape.

1285
01:06:33,873 --> 01:06:41,336
So all of my characters, or the main characters that I usually do, are based on some sort of base shape.

1286
01:06:41,857 --> 01:06:45,358
And then I try to squish them and see what that makes them do.

1287
01:06:46,028 --> 01:06:49,329
So I have one character that I like in particular called Alphonse.

1288
01:06:49,690 --> 01:06:51,310
I designed him to be a pear.

1289
01:06:51,991 --> 01:06:52,671
That's what he was.

1290
01:06:54,012 --> 01:06:59,294
And part of his personality came from just trying to see him run.

1291
01:06:59,314 --> 01:07:03,276
Because, you know, he was a big guy.

1292
01:07:03,516 --> 01:07:11,120
But it was interesting because I started thinking about how does the mechanics work?

1293
01:07:11,200 --> 01:07:14,001
Because he had like a large, bulbous...

1294
01:07:15,734 --> 01:07:18,897
Well, bottom and let's just say that.

1295
01:07:19,998 --> 01:07:24,181
But I started thinking about it and I realized that this doesn't make sense

1296
01:07:24,281 --> 01:07:26,103
and not for his anatomy.

1297
01:07:26,283 --> 01:07:26,943
Why is that?

1298
01:07:27,744 --> 01:07:30,566
And eventually it hit me that he's a robot.

1299
01:07:31,447 --> 01:07:35,450
And because he's a robot, that implies a lot of the way he acts

1300
01:07:35,551 --> 01:07:36,651
and the way he does things.

1301
01:07:36,732 --> 01:07:38,553
And I ended up doing that with all the characters.

1302
01:07:40,330 --> 01:07:44,472
I had a main character whose face was just kind of a big oval,

1303
01:07:46,093 --> 01:07:48,434
and to kind of even that out I gave him a big hat.

1304
01:07:48,514 --> 01:07:51,976
But because I gave him the hat, it gave him a lot of expressive traits.

1305
01:07:52,256 --> 01:07:56,199
One of the reasons why he ended up being really shy and kind of cowardly

1306
01:07:56,279 --> 01:07:59,140
was because he had to interact with his hat.

1307
01:07:59,200 --> 01:08:01,441
What do you do with it? Well, you pull it down over your head.

1308
01:08:03,173 --> 01:08:09,522
It's, I feel like shape and just squishing them and using them and throwing them around,

1309
01:08:10,063 --> 01:08:12,607
that's a way to get to know your character.

1310
01:08:14,130 --> 01:08:15,011
I think that's about all I got.

1311
01:08:19,651 --> 01:08:21,633
Hi, this is a question for Richard.

1312
01:08:22,313 --> 01:08:24,635
So your work is a lot of really beautiful line work

1313
01:08:24,655 --> 01:08:26,457
with like a solid color underneath.

1314
01:08:26,877 --> 01:08:28,298
I'm just wondering from like more

1315
01:08:28,318 --> 01:08:30,020
of a technical execution standpoint,

1316
01:08:30,040 --> 01:08:31,981
like how do you tackle designs that ask for

1317
01:08:32,642 --> 01:08:33,923
like unique texture?

1318
01:08:34,163 --> 01:08:35,725
Or is that something that you ever encounter

1319
01:08:35,825 --> 01:08:36,505
during your work?

1320
01:08:36,885 --> 01:08:40,569
And you have to like show texture in a flat color

1321
01:08:40,649 --> 01:08:42,911
or a line work without sort of painting.

1322
01:08:43,051 --> 01:08:44,292
Is that something that you do

1323
01:08:44,432 --> 01:08:45,613
or do you have ways to get around it?

1324
01:08:46,648 --> 01:08:55,432
I think that the line work and the way I'm approaching art at the moment is interesting for me, just as an artist, so I've started doing it over the last couple of years.

1325
01:08:56,152 --> 01:09:01,175
Also I'm fortunate enough at our studio that our creative director's a big comic fan.

1326
01:09:01,255 --> 01:09:06,417
Neil Druckmann's a massive comic nerd, so he loves seeing that stuff and he's able to read it really well.

1327
01:09:07,417 --> 01:09:13,960
We're also working on projects where things are in known quantity, you know, jeans, sneakers.

1328
01:09:16,091 --> 01:09:19,752
I don't know how many dudes I drew with machine guns, but they get it.

1329
01:09:19,792 --> 01:09:21,413
It's an army boot, it's army pants.

1330
01:09:22,013 --> 01:09:25,814
So once again, I'm collecting reference and I'm talking to those character modelers,

1331
01:09:25,874 --> 01:09:27,094
so everyone's on the same page.

1332
01:09:27,154 --> 01:09:30,735
By the time I spit out those lineups of concepts,

1333
01:09:31,816 --> 01:09:33,316
everyone understands what they're looking at,

1334
01:09:33,516 --> 01:09:36,797
because we've sat around and we've talked about what kind of materials we can execute on.

1335
01:09:37,737 --> 01:09:41,759
You chat to technical riggers about secondary motion for your army guys,

1336
01:09:41,839 --> 01:09:45,240
and your material artists about the difference between a...

1337
01:09:46,025 --> 01:09:48,887
Fatigue and a hand grenade or whatever else is gonna be there

1338
01:09:49,228 --> 01:09:53,471
So I'm very lucky in that regard that we have that open conversation. There are other characters where

1339
01:09:54,172 --> 01:09:59,876
You know, you have to paint the bejesus out of it your photo bashing hell out of it for those that played uncharted 4

1340
01:10:00,737 --> 01:10:02,399
There's a couple of characters. I worked on

1341
01:10:03,660 --> 01:10:06,762
That are you know executed to a borderline photo

1342
01:10:07,383 --> 01:10:13,208
rendering state the old adventurer who passes away in the mansion

1343
01:10:13,428 --> 01:10:13,928
spoilers

1344
01:10:15,639 --> 01:10:20,903
There's an old adventurer. So for that one you had to take a different tact. So that's very much photo bashed

1345
01:10:22,484 --> 01:10:27,528
Does it answer your question? Yeah, so like you kind of take a different way to approach it instead of the line art

1346
01:10:27,568 --> 01:10:30,089
if you need a texture work, yeah, I think I think I've

1347
01:10:31,270 --> 01:10:36,674
It made sense to me because I'm already trying to be incredibly social on the floor and with the rest of the character department

1348
01:10:36,714 --> 01:10:42,758
right and I find that things go a lot more smoothly by being that way and then all of a sudden it didn't make sense to

1349
01:10:42,818 --> 01:10:44,620
Be rendering the hell out of everything

1350
01:10:45,187 --> 01:10:48,168
So, I mean, everyone that needs to know just sat down and looked at the reference,

1351
01:10:48,929 --> 01:10:53,471
and now I'm photo bashing that reference back into something, you know, it didn't make any sense.

1352
01:10:53,511 --> 01:10:54,932
So what's left to decide?

1353
01:10:55,092 --> 01:10:58,734
Shape, language, the weighting of the character, where these elements are going to be.

1354
01:10:59,455 --> 01:11:03,877
So for me, I sort of fell into this line art, comic book type stuff.

1355
01:11:04,537 --> 01:11:06,238
And plus, it's really fun and it's super quick.

1356
01:11:06,258 --> 01:11:08,720
You can just, you know, you can bash them out really fast.

1357
01:11:09,200 --> 01:11:09,760
All right. Thank you.

1358
01:11:10,260 --> 01:11:13,663
I do think that's a super important point about concept art, though, is that it's not

1359
01:11:13,683 --> 01:11:15,765
about making finished illustrations.

1360
01:11:16,306 --> 01:11:19,549
It's very tempting to finish these things and polish them because it's all about your

1361
01:11:19,629 --> 01:11:19,769
art.

1362
01:11:20,189 --> 01:11:24,994
You're part of this larger pipeline, and so you need to communicate just enough to whoever's

1363
01:11:25,034 --> 01:11:25,995
next in that pipeline.

1364
01:11:26,815 --> 01:11:31,277
And, yeah, I've often found that when I was younger in the industry, I would just painstakingly

1365
01:11:31,357 --> 01:11:35,558
render these things because I wanted the accolades of having beautifully painted a thing.

1366
01:11:35,978 --> 01:11:40,179
But I could have just as easily done line art, flats, and then call out textures, and

1367
01:11:40,239 --> 01:11:43,060
would have communicated it just as well, possibly better.

1368
01:11:43,740 --> 01:11:45,200
So being a concept artist, I know.

1369
01:11:45,680 --> 01:11:51,182
You go to ArtStation and start looking through portfolios where everything's just polished to a T,

1370
01:11:51,582 --> 01:11:56,864
but sometimes it's a bunch of polish on a bad design. I'd rather see an unfinished good design

1371
01:11:56,904 --> 01:12:02,906
that communicates well, rather than something that's been painted for a week on end that's useless.

1372
01:12:04,226 --> 01:12:09,067
That is the most important thing I think anyone has said today. It's really confusing for concept

1373
01:12:09,147 --> 01:12:12,388
artists. You look at CGTalk, you look at ArtStation, you see all this marvelous art.

1374
01:12:13,520 --> 01:12:14,562
It's not about that.

1375
01:12:14,802 --> 01:12:15,844
It's about making a game.

1376
01:12:16,205 --> 01:12:20,492
So, you know, sorry, I can't emphasize that here.

1377
01:12:20,593 --> 01:12:21,454
That's a very good point.

1378
01:12:21,715 --> 01:12:22,616
You're making a video game,

1379
01:12:22,636 --> 01:12:23,979
you're not making an art exhibition.

1380
01:12:24,059 --> 01:12:25,281
Thank you.

1381
01:12:27,516 --> 01:12:30,419
Hi, this is question for Laura.

1382
01:12:30,820 --> 01:12:35,365
When you mentioned you just combined some features of face of different

1383
01:12:35,405 --> 01:12:40,031
emotions like emotions like like like like a surprise or sorrow.

1384
01:12:40,832 --> 01:12:45,578
You combine them like randomly or there's a rule behind

1385
01:12:47,480 --> 01:12:54,044
There's definitely thought on which aspects of which one you might combine, and that really

1386
01:12:54,104 --> 01:12:59,468
comes down to sort of performance and your own feeling about what it ought to be.

1387
01:12:59,508 --> 01:13:02,790
That's why I say keep a mirror around, so if you're thinking like, okay, I have this

1388
01:13:03,290 --> 01:13:05,031
situation that I want to make an expression for.

1389
01:13:07,232 --> 01:13:08,833
and what face does my character make?

1390
01:13:08,893 --> 01:13:11,533
And so you can kind of test it out in the mirror.

1391
01:13:12,133 --> 01:13:14,454
And once you kind of have something there,

1392
01:13:14,474 --> 01:13:21,295
you can think, okay, maybe this character feels derisive

1393
01:13:21,395 --> 01:13:23,215
compared to the person he's talking to.

1394
01:13:23,435 --> 01:13:24,275
He's looking down at them,

1395
01:13:24,295 --> 01:13:25,976
so maybe he's kind of sneering

1396
01:13:26,016 --> 01:13:26,956
with a little bit of disgust.

1397
01:13:26,976 --> 01:13:31,417
So you're adding a bit of a lip curl to that face.

1398
01:13:32,477 --> 01:13:34,377
So it's really, it's an artistic tool.

1399
01:13:34,417 --> 01:13:35,077
It's not like.

1400
01:13:35,880 --> 01:13:42,184
A plus B equals C. It's a way to sort of break it down and think about what you're doing.

1401
01:13:42,204 --> 01:13:44,785
Yeah, that's about it.

1402
01:13:44,825 --> 01:13:47,547
So you just like try to be an actor?

1403
01:13:47,867 --> 01:13:51,769
Basically, yeah. It's what animators do. It is just what they do.

1404
01:13:52,729 --> 01:13:56,771
And they've known this for a long time, so this would be not very new to them.

1405
01:13:56,872 --> 01:14:00,433
But for 2D artists, I found it was new to me anyway.

1406
01:14:00,453 --> 01:14:01,634
Okay, thank you.

1407
01:14:04,296 --> 01:14:05,236
My question is for Simon.

1408
01:14:05,997 --> 01:14:09,237
You had a very long development process of almost 10 years.

1409
01:14:09,577 --> 01:14:13,518
So I was wondering how often you had to reiterate your main characters

1410
01:14:13,579 --> 01:14:15,879
or any of your characters in terms of design

1411
01:14:16,019 --> 01:14:19,180
and how important it was for bringing other artists to look at your work.

1412
01:14:19,660 --> 01:14:23,601
Yeah, it was nine months. No, nine years minus one month.

1413
01:14:24,301 --> 01:14:25,882
So it was quite some time.

1414
01:14:27,722 --> 01:14:31,423
The main character actually was a point of contention because...

1415
01:14:33,238 --> 01:14:36,279
It was literally one of the first things I made

1416
01:14:36,319 --> 01:14:38,740
for the project and after working on it

1417
01:14:38,760 --> 01:14:40,660
for maybe five years and realizing

1418
01:14:40,700 --> 01:14:42,160
that it's not really all that good,

1419
01:14:43,181 --> 01:14:45,901
you can't just trade out about 200 animations.

1420
01:14:46,481 --> 01:14:49,462
So what we did instead was that we compensated

1421
01:14:49,522 --> 01:14:51,042
by making the animations more fluid

1422
01:14:51,822 --> 01:14:55,023
and giving more emphasis on what you did.

1423
01:14:55,663 --> 01:14:57,784
So we did a talk yesterday where we showed

1424
01:14:58,604 --> 01:15:00,244
the difference between the running animations

1425
01:15:00,324 --> 01:15:02,065
on the beginning and afterwards.

1426
01:15:02,747 --> 01:15:07,968
showing how you did turn cycles and you added emphasis to movement when you flew and that

1427
01:15:08,008 --> 01:15:08,508
sort of thing.

1428
01:15:10,848 --> 01:15:16,730
In terms of the game itself, the good thing about the game was that we didn't do the game

1429
01:15:16,830 --> 01:15:19,050
with tilesets, we did it with assets.

1430
01:15:19,790 --> 01:15:22,991
So it was big pixel chunks that you could put anywhere.

1431
01:15:23,711 --> 01:15:27,312
And incidentally, that also means that they're fairly easy to replace.

1432
01:15:29,272 --> 01:15:29,813
We did...

1433
01:15:31,838 --> 01:15:37,640
very big pieces, and mostly the really old stuff

1434
01:15:37,680 --> 01:15:40,301
was in the very middle of the game.

1435
01:15:40,841 --> 01:15:42,821
So when you're flying through that part,

1436
01:15:42,861 --> 01:15:47,003
the quality is kind of, mm, there.

1437
01:15:47,523 --> 01:15:50,804
The tutorial levels were sort of late development,

1438
01:15:50,864 --> 01:15:53,365
and then the very last stages, I think I did something

1439
01:15:53,385 --> 01:15:56,806
like a 3,000 pixel scroll, just to show

1440
01:15:56,846 --> 01:15:59,547
that I could do something proper for once.

1441
01:15:59,567 --> 01:15:59,607
So.

1442
01:16:02,368 --> 01:16:05,070
I feel like that was a good way to compensate.

1443
01:16:05,330 --> 01:16:06,991
Sure, the sprite is fairly old,

1444
01:16:07,071 --> 01:16:09,633
but animation is always appreciated.

1445
01:16:09,713 --> 01:16:11,174
So that was how we solved that.

1446
01:16:12,075 --> 01:16:12,355
Thank you.

1447
01:16:12,375 --> 01:16:17,719
I'd like to thank the panel for a wonderful presentation.

1448
01:16:17,899 --> 01:16:20,381
And if there are any further audience questions,

1449
01:16:20,421 --> 01:16:22,382
the breakout room across the hall is available.

1450
01:16:22,402 --> 01:16:24,424
Awesome, thank you. Thank you.

